DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(88)90026-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X88900268
AB  - Generally, utilities issue straight fixed-rate preferreds, industrials issue convertible fixed-rate preferreds, and financials issue adjustable-rate preferreds. The corresponding announcement-period common stock abnormal returns are economically insignificant for utilities, negative and significant at the 0.05 level for industrials, and positive and significant at the 0.10 level for financials. Information effects explain the cross-sectional results for industrial firms, but tax benefits and/or regulatory conditions are more likely explanations of the results documented for financial corporations and utilities. Returns to preferred stockholders support neither the wealth redistribution- hypothesis nor the price-pressure hypothesis.
